  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">I analyze the relationship between quantum chromodynamics (QCD) and generalized bag-type models. By functionally integrating over gluon variables and making a mean-field approximation, QCD can be reduced to a relativistic model in which quantized quarks move in a multi-bi-Grassmann-valued background gauge field. The dynamics of the background field is related to the mean quark motions by a classical variational principle, in which the gauge-invariant gluon effective action appears as the gluon kinetic term; formally, the model closely resembles the semiclassical out-in approximation to general relativity. By making an additional quark source charge approximation, the model can be further reduced to a form in which the quarks couple to a pair of classical abelian background gauge fields obeying effective action dynamics. Both formulations are natural generalizations of a non-relativistic effective action model in which the mean fields of static source charges are confined in bag-like domains. The exact QCD partition function can be formally developed in a series expansion around the solution of the abelian background field model, which serves as a zeroth-order binding approximation.</subfield>
